<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06297047 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06297047 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Planning a Halloween party for the kids? This sampler offers fun and easytricks for making their own treats; Party tips for the Ghouls Night Out:  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Food  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MONSTER BASH  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO><TEXT>     (check) The more you involve the children in planning, the more successfulthe party.;   (check) Your child can invite the number of children equal tohis or her age. If she's 8 years old, she invites no more than eight guests;if he's 3, he asks three.;   (check) When issuing invitations, be sure theparents know all the facts. Should the child wear a costume? Will you serve asnack or a meal? Will the party be outdoors?;   (check) Each child should havea treat to take home.;   (check) A moldy-oldie idea from yesteryear: Kids lovenut cups. Yes, nut cups. Your youngster fills them with peanuts and Halloweencandy.; -- Suzanne Martinson, Scripps; Howard News Service; CARAMEL APPLES; 6medium apples; 6 tablespoons granola, chopped peanuts or chopped candy-coatedchocolate candies; 1 14-ounce package vanilla caramels; 3 tablespoons water;1/4 cup creamy peanut butter; 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon;  Poke a woodenstick in the stem end of each apple.;   Using 1 tablespoon of granola, peanutsor chopped candy-coated chocolate candies for each mound, make 6 mounds about3 inches apart on waxed paper.;   In a saucepan combine caramels, water,peanut butter and cinnamon and cook over low heat about 20 minutes or untilcaramels are melted and mixture is smooth.;   Remove from heat. Dip each applein the hot caramel mixture and spoon mixture over the apple until it iscompletely coated.;   Hold the apple right side up by the stick for a second,then place it stick-side-up on one of the mounds of granola. Turn the apple soall the granola sticks to it.;   Refrigerate about 1 hour or until the caramelcoating is firm.;   Variation: CHOCOLATY CARAMEL APPLES -- Use only 2tablespoons of water. Use 1/4 cup chocolate chips in place of the peanutbutter and chocolate caramels in place of the vanilla caramels.;   -- From&quot;Betty Crocker's New Boys and Girls Cookbook,&quot; 1990, Betty Crocker; HALLOWEEN;ORANGE SHERBET FREEZE; 6 medium oranges; 1 quart orange sherbet; 18 candycorns;  Place each orange on its side. Use a serrated knife to cut a sliceabout 1/2 inch from the stem. Repeat the process for all the oranges. Run aserrated knife around the inside edge of each orange to loosen orangesections. Remove orange sections with a spoon.;   Dry orange skins thoroughlywith a dish cloth. Decorate oranges with black markers so that they look likejack-o'-lanterns.;   Spoon sherbet into hollowed orange skins. Garnish the topof each orange with three candy corns.;   Freeze oranges for at least 4 hours.Remove a few minutes before serving to allow to soften slightly. Makes 6oranges at 216 calories per serving.;   Note: Save orange juice and sectionsfor a cool snack.; -- From &quot;Young Chef's Nutrition Guide and Cookbook&quot; byCarolyn E. Moore, Ph.D., R.D., Mimi Kerr and Robert Shulman, M.D., 1990,Barron; JACK-O'-LANTERN PIZZAS;  Processed American cheese slices;  Pizzasauce;  English muffins, split;  Olive slices;  Shredded cheese;  Green bellpepper strips;  Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Cut cheese slices into trianglesfor eyes, small circles for noses and half-moons for mouths forjack-o'-lantern faces. Spread pizza sauce on muffin halves and place on abaking sheet. Bake for 15 minutes.;   Place muffins on individual servingplates. Arrange cheese cut-outs on muffins for face. Add olive slices foreyeballs, shredded cheese for hair and green pepper strip for stem. Serveimmediately.; -- From &quot;Kids Cook With; Stuffee,&quot; from the Pittsburgh;Children's Museum.; JACK-O'-LANTERN CAKE; 1 18 1/4-ounce package spice orcarrot cake mix with pudding;  Creamy Frosting:; 3 cups confectioners' sugar;1/3 cup margarine or butter, softened; 2 tablespoons milk; 1 1/2 teaspoonsvanilla;  Red and yellow food coloring;  Flat black jelly candies, see note; Candy corn;  Prepare cake according to package directions using 2 8- or 9-inchround pans that have been greased and floured. Cool layers completely andremove cakes from pan.;   Frosting: Mix confectioners' sugar and margarine ina medium bowl. Stir in milk and vanilla and beat frosting until smooth and ofspreading consistency. If frosting is too thick, add a little more milk. Iffrosting is too thin, add a little more confectioners' sugar.;   Tint frostingby using a few drops of red and yellow food color. Start slow, adding moredrops to get the color of orange you like.;   Fill the layers and frost thecake.;   Make a jack-o'-lantern face with the black jelly candy and candycorn.;   Note: Licorice can be substituted for black jelly candies.;   -- From&quot;Betty Crocker's; New Boys and Girls Cookbook.&quot;; HALLOWEEN PUMPKIN; COOKIESPROJECT; 1/2 cup (1 stick) butter or margarine; 1 cup cooked pumpkin; 1 cupsugar; 1 egg, slightly beaten; 1 teaspoon milk; 1 teaspoon vanilla; 2 cupsall-purpose or unbleached flour; 2 teaspoons baking powder; 1 teaspoon bakingsoda; 1 teaspoon cinnamon; 1/2 teaspoon salt; 1 cup semisweet chocolate chips;1/2 cup nuts, optional;  Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Place the butter ormargarine in a heat-proof glass dish. Cover and microwave on high for 30seconds. In a large bowl, mix together pumpkin, sugar, melted butter ormargarine, beaten egg, milk and vanilla. (You can use an electric mixer forthis step, but when you add the flour, the dough will get stiff and you canbeat it better by hand.);   In separate bowl, combine flour, baking powder,baking soda, cinnamon and salt. Add to pumpkin mixture and mix until smooth.Stir in chocolate chips and nuts. Drop from a teaspoon onto lightly greasedbaking sheet. Line up about 1 1/2 inches apart. Bake for 10 to 12 minutes, oruntil golden brown. Cool on baking sheet for 2 minutes. Remove to wire rack tofinish cooling. Store in an airtight container. Makes about 36 cookies.;   --From &quot;Cooking Wizardry; for Kids&quot; by Margaret Kenda; and Phyllis S. Williams,1990,; Barron; FIESTA CHILI FOR CHILDREN; 1 medium onion, chopped; 1 poundground beef; 1 tablespoon chili powder; 1/2 teaspoon garlic salt;  Dash of redpepper sauce; 1 14 1/2-ounce can tomatoes, undrained; 1 16-ounce can redbeans, undrained; 2 tablespoons shredded Cheddar cheese;  Cook and stir onionwith ground beef over medium heat in a large saucepan for 10 minutes, or untilground beef is brown. Pour into a strainer to drain off fat. Return beef andonion to pan.;   Stir in the chili powder, garlic salt, hot sauce andundrained tomatoes. Chop up tomatoes with mixing spoon. Heat mixture toboiling; lower heat and simmer 30 minutes. Stir in undrained beans. Cook 30minutes longer. Ladle chili into soup bowls; top with Cheddar. Makes 4servings.;   -- From &quot;Betty Crocker's New Boys and Girls Cookbook&quot;  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911023  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  1,150  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, October 23, 199100297047,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  0  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>